    "body": "This is supposed to fix most issues regarding manipulating `moment-timezone`-d moments across DST. Unfortunately the built-in Date still has the same issues.\r\n\r\nThe main idea of the change is:\r\n* create low-level unit getters and setters that don't care about offset.\r\n* Create higher level setter, that handles updating offset.\r\n* Handle keep-time cases (changing the time across DST while wanting to preserve the hour/minutes), in which it is impossible (no such hour/minute in the current timezone)\r\n* change updateOffset/zone api (zone's second arg wasn't working at all before, so I'm pretty confident no code is broken) \r\n* Setting the hour now keeps the time (that is we'll try to actually set the hour to the one you say :))\r\n* startOf now works across DST\r\n\r\nCorresponding `moment-timezone` PR will show up soon\r\n\r\nEDIT: https://github.com/moment/moment-timezone/pull/70",

    "body": "No tests for this yet, but just wanna open this up to see if there's interest in merging. If there is, I'll add some tests/docs/cleanup.\r\n\r\nWe need the ability to parse a date relative to another date. For example, given the input \"3:33 PM\", I want to be able to parse this value relative to two days from now, instead of the current date/time. This allows you to do the following:\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nmoment.relative(moment(\"2014-03-29\"), \"3:33 PM\", \"h:mm A\")\r\n```",

    "body": "This patch improves performance of `leftZeroFill` by avoiding lots of unnecessary string concatenations. http://jsperf.com/zero-filling-full\r\n\r\nImprovements in Node.JS:\r\n\r\n- 10% faster when no zero filling is needed\r\n- Same speed when 1 zero fill is needed\r\n- 3x faster when 5 zero fills are needed\r\n- ~2x faster when 2 zero fills are needed\r\n\r\n<hr>\r\n\r\nI also changed the comment because the jsperf linked was incorrect - it doesn't use the code from the library and doesn't even use a zero fill argument. It also uses randomization which gives random results - the run to get least needed zero filling would win regardless of the actual performance of the implementation.",
